Kerri is the founder of CTZNWELL, a movement that is democratizing well-being for all. A descendant of generations of firemen and first responders, Kerri has dedicated her life to kicking down doors and fighting for justice. She’s been teaching yoga for over 20 years and is known for making waves in the wellness industry by challenging norms, disrupting systems and mobilizing people to act. 

A community organizer, wellness activist and author of the forthcoming book American Detox: The Myth of Wellness and How We Can Truly Heal, Kerri is recognized across communities for her inspired work to bridge transformational practice with social justice. She’s been instrumental in translating the practices of wellbeing into social and political action, working in collaboration with community organizers, spiritual leaders and policy makers to transform our systems from the inside out. Her leadership has inspired a movement that is actively organizing around issues of racial and economic justice, healthcare as a human right, civic engagement and more.

Kerri is a student of abolition, anti-racism, ableism and decolonization. She works diligently to dismantle oppression within herself and the systems and culture she is a part of. She works in support and solidarity with BIPOC leaders and organizations to explore how to work across lines of difference to advance equity and build community resilience.

The definition of emergence is “the process of coming into view or becoming exposed after being concealed.” Essential to this process is the practice of unlearning and unraveling ourselves from the toxic ideologies that have shaped us and held us back from our whole selves. Only then can we become who we are beyond who we have been told we are supposed to be and emerge into our full possibility and potential. 

"The language of emergence is listening, allowing oneself to always be moved and changed, tuning in to the wisdom that is beyond words and language. And remembering—always remembering that we are not the first and we will not be the last. There will always be those who came before us and those who are yet to come. Time is not linear, which means we are the past, present, and future. We are the ancestors and we are descendants. We are the teachers and we are the students. We are the end of one thing and the beginning of another." (American Detox: The Myth of Wellness and How We Can Truly Heal)

As I’m wrapping up my year with one day of work left, I’ve been gently reflecting. When we take stock of our year in big ways it can feel disappointing or disheartening. Our brains can be more drawn to our shortcomings or what we are looking forward to doing NEXT. So much happens in a year. It goes far beyond big achievements or shortcomings. When I look back on my year of course I’ll remember the birth of my baby, the release of my book, the challenges in my relationship, the trip to Disney world. I also want to acknowledge the moment my daughter’s teacher congratulated me on my book because she’d been talking about it in school, the moment I first hit dinner made and felt peace with having 3 children, the moments I felt care from the people around me, the small moments of growth and healing with clients, the small moments of growth and healing within myself. There wasn’t as much space to slowdown but the moments I was able felt so very tender. I’m holding on to all of this tightly as I ease toward the end of this year. What are the moments you’re holding?
✨ What did slowing down look like this year?
✨ What were some moments of safety?
✨ What were some moments of play?
✨ When did you feel held or supported this year? By whom?
✨ What did healing look like this year? Where in your life does that work show up?
✨ What were some difficult moments you moved through this year?
✨ What were some moments of ease or softness?
✨ What made you proud (big or small)?
✨ What will you take with you in to the new year? What will you leave behind?

🤓Judith Butler is a new favourite Thinker.  I love this quote because I think that the acknowledgement of interdependence as a fact of human (and non-human) life, opens our minds towards cooperation, caring, and giving - not simply as acts of kindness towards others, but towards oneself as well.

More from Judith Butler:
“We are all, if we stand, supported by any number of things. Even coming to see you today—the pavement allowed me to move, and so did my shoes, my orthotics, and the long hours spent by my physical therapist. His labor is in my walk, as it were. I wouldn’t have been able to get here without any of those wonderful technologies and supporting relations.

Acknowledging dependency as a condition of who any of us happens to be is difficult enough. But the larger task is to affirm social and ecological interdependence, which is regularly misrecognized as well.”

Source: New Yorker Interview with Judith Butler - February 9, 2020.

When I first experienced moments of calm after decades of feeling anxious, it felt so unsafe that I found myself shifting back into a state of fight-or-flight.

When I first experienced moments of contentment after years of striving for external success, it felt so unsafe that I started overworking again.

When I first experienced moments of joy after months of living with depression, it felt so unsafe that my mood spiralled downwards again.

Because when we’re living in a state of chronic or traumatic stress, our nervous systems perceive anything unfamiliar as unsafe.

Even if we long for calmness and contentment and joy, there’s often a strange comfort in the anxiety, shame and unworthiness we’ve become accustomed to.

Because our nervous systems know these painful feelings.

They feel safe.

But pleasure? Relaxation? Joy? Ease? Compassion? Love?

These are often new experiences for our nervous systems.

And new feels uncertain and unpredictable and unsafe.

And yet, slowly and gently  we can teach our nervous systems that’s it’s safe to feel joy. To feel peace. To feel love.

This is why I created the Tiny Moments of Rest workshop. 

To give you one tiny but powerful relaxation practice everyday for 30 days so you can lovingly and tenderly teach your nervous system that you’re safe. 

Safe to stop striving.

Coffee?” People know how much I appreciate iced coffee and the role of baristas in community mental health. If your answer is yes to the second question, how will your relationship to coffee change knowing this? On July 5, 1852, Frederick Douglass (1818-1895) gave a speech to the Rochester Ladies’ Anti-Slavery Society in Rochester, New York. This speech is known as "What to the Slave is the Fourth of July?" 

Douglass was born into slavery in 1818 in Maryland, and escaped to the North in 1838. In 1845, he published 📚 Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, and went on to become perhaps the most well known abolitionist of his time. 

📍In his speech, he says: 

“What, to the American slave, is your 4th of July? I answer; a day that reveals to him, more than all other days in the year, the gross injustice and cruelty to which he is the constant victim. To him, your celebration is a sham; your boasted liberty, an unholy license; your national greatness, swelling vanity; your sound of rejoicing are empty and heartless; your denunciation of tyrants brass fronted impudence; your shout of liberty and equality, hollow mockery; your prayers and hymns, your sermons and thanks-givings, with all your religious parade and solemnity, are to him, mere bombast, fraud, deception, impiety, and hypocrisy -- a thin veil to cover up crimes which would disgrace a nation of savages. There is not a nation on the earth guilty of practices more shocking and bloody than are the people of the United States, at this very hour.”

This speech was given 9 years before start of the Civil War in 1861.

We leave you this quote from Douglass’ speech on this 4th of July to invite you think about what notion of freedom the United States was founded upon. Was it a freedom for all? Or is freedom something that is yet to come?

Sometimes life pulls the rug out from under us.  When that happens, our instinct is to cling, to find ground, to reach for something we can rely on. We scramble, we run, we do anything to escape the vulnerability and discomfort of what is. For me, it was the lie of separation and security that kept me fending for myself and minding my business. I curated my life in a safe and small bubble, insulated from everything and everyone around me. I thought I could control every outcome, defend every move, anticipate every next step. But it only left me more alone and isolated. Pema Chödrön says that “all addictions stem from this moment when we meet our edge and we just can’t stand it.”
 
But difficult moments are also an invitation to courage. They are often the moment when you realize that you can choose to do something different. Instead of conquering your fears you move into relationship with them. When we learn to get comfortable with the uncomfortable, we are released from its grip. What might appear on the surface as chaos is actually freedom—freedom from the struggle against the fundamental ambiguity of simply being human. The one truth—the thing we know beyond a doubt—is that nothing is fixed and to be human is a dynamic experience that is ever changing. Permanence is a myth we buy into because we fear its opposite. The only way to get free is to let go.

LOSS. GRIEF. TRAUMA.

People are hurting everywhere and grief shows up at every turn and in every corner of the world.

There's no escaping grief and eventually, grief will find its way into everyone's life.

And when it does, it can feel as if everything is tainted and nothing looks the same.

Grief shows up for a reason and one of the biggest reasons is love but it doesn't change the fact that the journey of grief is hard.

If you're grieving I know you're sad in ways that are difficult to explain. I know you're so sad it hurts and the pain rests in your bones. 

I know you have a hole and void in your life that's impossible to completely fill. Because there's no replacing someone you love. 

There's no fixing grief and you're not experiencing a problem that can be solved. So I'm not going to try to "fix" you or cheer you up with pleasantries or small talk. 

I'm not going to ask how you are or expect you to do things that might feel impossible right now. 

I'm not going to tell you everything happens for a reason or push you to get over it or move on.

I'm not going to tell you it's not that bad or expect you to be the person you were before life turned upside down.

Instead I'm going to hold your hand. I'm going to sit with you in your pain and just listen to you while acknowledging your grief. 

I'm going to support you and love you while reminding you that all you're experiencing is normal and that it's okay to have tough, unraveling days.

I'm not going to expect you to get up and conquer your grief. To smile and pretend you're fine when everything has turned upside down.

Instead I will keep telling you your grief matters and I'm so incredibly proud of you for taking the smallest of steps in the midst of your pain. I'm going to tell you how proud I am of you for getting up and trying to move at all.

I'm holding space for you and sending love. Always.

Michele

Ladder 15 is the only known fire company to have reached the floor of impact on 9/11. My stepdad, Lt Joe Leavey and his men were on their way to WTC when they saw the plane hit the second tower. Without hesitation, he redirected them to T2 where they proceeded to run up 78 flights of stairs when so many were running down and out.

Today, I am writing and reflecting from Montgomery,AL where I am deepening my understanding/responsibility in the horrific and heartbreaking legacy of slavery. I cant help but think this is another kind of ground zero, one that is demanding a reckoning and reconcilation of epic proportions. While these wounds are markedly different, I can see and feel how the lie of separation and supremacy got us here - a nation wounded many times over and caught up in an endless cycle of violence. 

Since 9/11 alone, people of Arab and South Asian descent have been intimidated, surveilled, incarcerated, and killed in exponentially increasing numbers. Military service members have given and taken their lives through suicide. Families have been torn apart through brutal immigration policies and mass incarceration. Millions of Americans have been surveilled and harassed. Black and brown communities have been targeted by racist militarism turned inward through law enforcement. And too many of us have given into a culture of fear, distrust and division.

And it leaves me wondering what have we learned from the last 22 years since 9/11, or last 400+ years since the first enslaved Africans arrived in Virginia or 600+ years since white settlers began colonizing turtle island? Where has violence and militarism gotten us? How do we repair the harm at home and around the world? And how do we create the conditions for true safety and care for all people?

To #NeverForget is to reckon with and remember not just what happened that day, but all of the injustice and resilience that are a part of our complicated history - from colonization to slavery to mass incarceration to the war on terror. And it is an invitation to do something different - to honor the legacy of all those we have lost - not thru more violence and war - but thru a politics of care and justice.
